title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y:D]]></fr:tex> be two elements of a dcpo <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>; we say that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>way below</fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>, written <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\ll  y]]></fr:tex>, when for any directed subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\subseteq  D]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y\sqsubseteq  \bigsqcup {I}]]></fr:tex>, there exists <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in  I]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\sqsubseteq  z]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>(Adapted from <fr:link
type="local"
href="dejong-2023-thesis.xml"
addr="dejong-2023-thesis"
title="Domain theory in constructive and predicative univalent foundations">Tom de Jong’s thesis</fr:link>.)</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
